WorldForge — Feature Specification v0.1
A self-hosted, AI-integrated worldbuilding wiki for small creative teams

Design Principles
Before the feature list, a few constraints that should govern every decision:

Wife test: Every feature must be usable by a non-technical person on an iPhone with no onboarding. If it requires knowing what a "slug" or "backlink" is, the UI has failed.
SRE sanity: Simple deployment first. One compose file, one config, done. Complexity earns its place later.
AI as collaborator, not crutch: AI features surface suggestions; humans always approve. Nothing auto-modifies content without confirmation.
Your data, always: Plain-text-readable storage. No proprietary binary formats. Export must be a first-class feature, not an afterthought.


1. Core Architecture
Storage

Primary content store: Markdown files with YAML frontmatter, stored on the local filesystem. This preserves Obsidian compatibility and ensures your existing vault can be imported directly.
Metadata/index store: A lightweight embedded database (SQLite is the natural fit for "simple first") for entity relationships, backlinks, tags, search indexes, and timeline data. Rebuilt from Markdown on startup if corrupted — source of truth is always the files.
Media store: Local filesystem directory, served statically. Images, maps, and file attachments organized by entity.
Vector store: Separate embeddings store (e.g., ChromaDB or SQLite-vec) for semantic search and AI context retrieval. Rebuilt on demand.

Deployment

Single Docker Compose stack: web server, backend API, and database in one file.
Optional: separate AI service container for local LLM (Ollama), disabled by default.
Exposed as a PWA (Progressive Web App) — installable on iPhone/iPad from Safari with full offline read access to cached content.
Reverse-proxy friendly (Caddy/Nginx config examples provided).

Auth

Simple invite-based user model. Owner creates accounts; no self-registration.
Session-based auth with persistent login on mobile.
Per-entity visibility: Public to all users / Private to owner / Hidden (exists but not visible to guests).
No OAuth complexity in v1 — add it later if needed.


2. Entity System
The data model is the heart of the tool. Every piece of lore is an Entity with a type, a Markdown body, YAML frontmatter metadata, and typed relationships to other entities.
Core Entity Types
TypeKey FieldsNotesCharacterFull name, aliases, status (alive/dead/unknown), physical description, personality traits, motivations, arc summary, faction memberships, relationships to other charactersRelationships are typed: ally, rival, family, romantic, mentor, unknownLocationName, location type (continent/region/city/building/etc.), parent location, population, climate/atmosphere, political control (faction), notable residents, descriptionHierarchy: World → Region → City → District → BuildingFactionName, type (government/guild/religion/cult/etc.), founding date, goals, rivals, allies, member characters, controlled locationsMagic System / TechnologyName, type, source/rules, limitations/costs, practitioners, associated artifactsRules field is critical — AI uses this for consistency checkingArtifact / ItemName, type, origin, current owner, history, magical/technical propertiesLore ArticleTitle, tags, freeform bodyCatch-all for anything that doesn't fit typed entities: historical events, religions, cultural practices, in-world texts
Schema Flexibility

Every entity type has a fixed core schema (the typed fields above) plus an open extensions block in YAML frontmatter for custom fields your specific world needs.
New entity types can be defined in a config file without code changes — the core types are just well-supported defaults.


3. Editing Experience
Editor

Rich WYSIWYG editor (ProseMirror-based) as the default — no Markdown syntax knowledge required for your wife.
Raw Markdown toggle for power users (you).
Autosave every 30 seconds and on navigation away.
Mobile-optimized: large tap targets, collapsible sections, bottom-sheet metadata panel.

Linking

Type [[ to get an inline entity picker — searches by name across all entity types.
Backlinks panel on every entity page showing all other entities that reference it.
Unresolved links (references to entities that don't exist yet) are highlighted and queued as stubs — a to-do list for your world.
Relationship graph auto-populated from both explicit schema fields (character's faction membership) and inline [[links]] in body text.

Media

Drag-and-drop image upload inline in the editor.
Image gallery per entity.
Map upload with pin annotations: upload a map image, place named pins, each pin links to a Location entity. No external map service required.
File attachments (PDFs, reference docs) per entity.


4. Navigation & Organization

Dashboard: Recent edits, stub queue, timeline snapshot, and an "AI needs your attention" tray (more below).
Entity browser: Filterable, sortable list by type, tag, faction, status. Works well on mobile.
Relationship graph: Visual node-edge graph of entities and their connections. Filterable by entity type and relationship type. Read-only in v1 (editing happens on entity pages, not in the graph).
Timeline: A horizontal chronology of in-world events. Events are either standalone Lore Articles or anchored to entity milestones (character birth/death, faction founding, artifact creation). Supports multiple in-world calendars with custom epoch definitions.
Tag system: Free-form tags on all entities, plus auto-generated system tags (e.g., #stub, #ai-flagged, #needs-review).
Full-text search: Fast, instant, covers all entity fields and body text.


5. Collaboration
Given the small trusted team model, this is deliberately simple:

Optimistic concurrent editing with last-write-wins and a visible "currently editing" indicator per entity (not full Google Docs CRDT in v1).
Edit history per entity — every save is versioned, diffable, and reversible.
Comments on any entity (threaded, resolvable) — important for async "I think this contradicts chapter 3" conversations.
Change feed: A shared activity log showing all edits, new entities, and AI suggestions from all users. Filterable.
No branching/merging in v1. Everyone works on the same canonical world state. Add it later if you find you need it (you probably won't for 2–5 people).


6. AI Features
This is where the tool differentiates itself. The AI layer is a service abstraction that routes to whichever LLM backend is configured — Anthropic API, OpenAI API, a local Ollama instance, or your existing MCP server via its tool interface.
6a. Lore Generation / Writing Assistance

Entity generation: Given a name and type, generate a draft entity with filled fields consistent with existing world lore. Always presented as a draft requiring approval before saving.
Prose assistance: In-editor selection → right-click → "Expand," "Summarize," "Rephrase in world voice," or "Continue." Operates on selected text with full entity context injected.
Stub filler: For unresolved [[links]], offer to draft the missing entity. One-click to review and accept.

6b. Semantic Search

All entity content is embedded on save.
Search bar has two modes: keyword (instant, SQLite FTS) and semantic (vector similarity, slightly slower). Toggle between them.
Semantic search answers questions like "who has a grudge against the crown?" or "what locations are associated with fire magic?" — not just keyword matches.
AI can be prompted to search your world to answer lore questions directly, with citations to the source entities.

6c. Auto-linking / Relationship Suggestions

On save, the AI scans the new/edited content and suggests [[links]] for entity names it recognizes that aren't already linked.
Suggests relationship additions: "This character profile mentions House Vaelthar three times but has no faction relationship recorded. Add it?"
Suggestions appear as non-blocking notifications, never auto-applied.

6d. Summarization

Entity summary: One-click "Summarize this character/location/faction" — generates a 2–3 sentence overview useful for quick reference during writing.
World state digest: A periodic (or on-demand) summary of recent changes to the world — useful for your wife to catch up after a busy call schedule without reading every edit.
Arc summary: Given a character, summarize their known story arc across all entities that reference them.

6e. Consistency Checking

This is the most novel feature. On demand (not automatic — too noisy otherwise), the AI audits a selected entity or the entire world for:

Factual contradictions: Character is stated as dead in one article and alive in another.
Rule violations: A magic system has an established cost/limitation that an artifact or character ability appears to ignore.
Timeline conflicts: An event references a character being in two places at once, or precedes their birth.
Orphaned references: Entities referenced in text but not formally linked.


Results presented as a flagged list, each with the conflicting passages and a suggested resolution. Human decides what to do.

AI Configuration

Settings panel: select provider (Anthropic / OpenAI / Ollama / MCP), enter API key or endpoint URL, select model.
Per-feature toggles — you can enable semantic search but disable auto-link suggestions if they're too noisy.
All AI prompts include a world context block: the system prompt is automatically populated with your world's name, genre, tone notes, and any "ground rules" you define (e.g., "This is a secondary world. There is no gunpowder. Magic has a blood cost."). This context travels with every AI call.


7. Import / Export

Import from Obsidian vault: Scan a directory of .md files, parse frontmatter, auto-detect entity types from folder structure or tags, create entities. Wikilinks become backlinks.
Export to Obsidian vault: Full round-trip. Your files stay yours.
Export to JSON: Full world snapshot for backup or migration.
Export to PDF/EPUB: Per-entity or full world export, formatted for readability. Useful for sharing with beta readers.
Export to Markdown archive: Flat directory of .md files, human-readable without any tooling.


8. What's Explicitly Out of Scope for v1
Keeping this list is as important as the feature list:

No VTT / virtual tabletop features (dice, initiative, battle maps)
No manuscript / novel draft editor (use Scrivener, iA Writer, or Obsidian for that — link out to it)
No public-facing world publishing (add in v2 if desired)
No mobile native apps (PWA covers the iPhone/iPad use case without App Store complexity)
No plugin system (your SRE instincts will tell you when it's time)
No multi-world isolation within one install (one install = one world; run multiple instances for multiple projects)


Suggested Build Phases
Phase 1 — The Useful Core
Entity CRUD, Markdown storage, YAML frontmatter, backlinks, full-text search, mobile-responsive UI, basic auth, Docker Compose deploy. Your wife can use this.
Phase 2 — The Differentiator
AI integration (generation, semantic search, auto-link suggestions), vector store, world context injection, MCP bridge.
Phase 3 — The Polish
Consistency checker, timeline UI, relationship graph, map pins, world state digest, Obsidian import/export.
Phase 4 — The Nice-to-Haves
Edit history/diff, comments, change feed, PDF/EPUB export, advanced entity schemas.
